<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Ok, here's the deal for those that didn't play eq (not sure if other games have mez)... <P>Mezzed mobs can't do anything until hit by some sort of damage.  You can stand right next to them and they won't hit anyone while mezzed.  This allows the group to kill one at a time.  It can be very effective.  AoE will break the mezzes when they hit them.<P>I have a request for mezzing classes:  don't introduce people to mez in a negative way by yelling at those who don't know.  In EQ I saw it handled in an polite and educational manner and things worked out much better.  I also saw enchanters who yelled and screamed, those times didn't work out well.  <P>Lets not start the class warfare in DAoC, please.  Mez is not an intuitive or realistic combat method, and it can be difficult for some to grasp in 15 seconds if they've never been exposed to it.  In EQ, pet classes have probably the most difficult time working with mez.  One day when I was playing my enchanter in eq, pet control was explained to a 1rst time mage in a few minutes by alts of high level mages and it worked well. If I or the other people had yelled at the mage, it would have ruined everyone's night and the mage wouldn't have learned and simply left the group.  Since I'd never played a pet class, I learned a great deal as well.  Heck, I didn't know how to control a pet in a group, so I was quite interested too.<P>So, be pleasant, work together, inform, experiment a bit, and have fun.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
